Comparative Overview of
Programming Languages
for Data-Intensive Projects

Author: Leo Osvald <losvald@purdue.edu>

Which programming languages?

  • 3/4 languages with APIs for Spark (useful for data-intensive computing):
    • Python - a multi-paradigm language with a focus on readability
    • R - a statistical computing language
    • Scala - a scalable JVM language that meets functional and object-oriented
  • Go (golang) - a pragmatic system language suitable for writing servers
    • one of the fastest growing languages (top 13, a winner in 2016/2009)
    • nearly as fast as C/C++, but easy to learn & master
    • used to write a number of recent production-grade data tools:
      • InfluxDB - scalable datastore for metrics, events & real-time analytics
      • Grafana - beautiful monitoring and metric analytics & dashboards
      • Prometheus - monitoring system and time series database
      • Docker, Kubernetes - virtualization, container deployment & management

Adapted from AIDA-light: High-Throughput Named-Entity Disambiguation by Dat Ba Nguyen et al., 2014

Analyzing context within certain distance

Core computation:

def neighboring_word_freqs(message, max_dist=10):
    words = tokenize(message.text)
    return [
        ((word1, word2, idx2 - idx1), 1)
        for idx1, word1 in enumerate(words)
        for idx2, word2 in enumerate(words)
        if 1 <= abs(idx1 - idx2) <= max_dist]

Analyzing context within certain distance

Core computation (Python):

def neighboring_word_freqs(message, max_dist=10):
    words = tokenize(message.text)
    return [
        ((word1, word2, idx2 - idx1), 1)
        for idx1, word1 in enumerate(words)
        for idx2, word2 in enumerate(words)
        if 1 <= abs(idx1 - idx2) <= max_dist]

PySpark job to parallelize it across the cluster:

df = spark_sql.read.json("twitter.json").query(
    "SELECT text WHERE lang='en'")
result = df.rdd\
           .flatMap(neighboring_word_freqs)\
           .reduceByKey(add)
for entry in result.toLocalIterator():
    (word1, word2, offset), freq = entry
    print(word1, word2, offset, entry)

When it gets more complicated...

  • generalize approach to multiple data sources that are
    • heteregenous (different treatment)
    • fetch data at different rate
  • support different analyses
  • continuous delivery of results

Question: Which languages to use for which parts?

Common features of Python, R, Scala, Go

  • popular in data science/analytics
  • "batteries included" - huge standard libraries (stable)
  • automatic Garbage Collection (no need to explicitly manage memory)
  • fully support reflection; inspection of properties at run-time
    • does a variable currently hold a text or a (bunch of) numbers?
    • can we iterate over contents of x, or can we call x
    • can we call train on an object that represents a model?
  • easy to experiment with (no need to setup up a project/package):
    • Go code (including tests) can be run as a script (compile+run)
    • Python/R/Scala have interactive shell (can also run as a script)

output source* source* bytecode+ binary^

  • Notes:
    • * one or more files without dependencies
    • + auto-downloaded dependencies with SBT/Ivy
    • ^ executable file with dependencies

    • only has to have the right operating system (Go)?

    • may need to manually install the dependencies (R/Python/Scala)?
      • unless the code is published in a package repository

Differences in languages features (overview)

  • implicit and explicit interfaces
  • dynamic vs static typing, duck typing
  • weakly vs strongly typed
  • built-in types
  • properties of data structures in the standard library
  • string manipulation and regular expressions
  • higher-order functions & non-local assignments
  • implementing design principles and patterns
  • concurrency
  • testing & benchmarking
  • interaction with data (relational, semi-structured, custom format)

Uniform handling of heterogeneous data

Suppose we need to process timestamp and text from:

  1. system log in dmesg format: [SECONDS_SINCE_STARTUP] MESSAGE
  2. (sent) emails, treating both the title and the body as text

A fragile workaround: preprocess by transforming to a common structure.

  • what if further processing on title and body is needed?
    • re-parse them (may be lossy!), or keep duplicates (separate and merged)?
  • convert system log's relative time to absolute time?
    • what if a subsequent analysis on relative (original) timestamp is required?
  • convert "Sent time" in email to a relative time (since system startup)?
    • what about the sender's timezone (may differ from the system's timezone)?

Interfacing with heterogeneous data

Suppose we need to process timestamp and text from:

  1. system log in dmesg format: [SECONDS_SINCE_STARTUP] MESSAGE
  2. (sent) emails, treating both the title and the body as text

A robust solution: precisely parse once, losslessly transform on the fly

  • multiple analyses can concurrently run without duplicating data
  • code is easier to maintain and more readable

Dynamic typing & heterogeneous data

If it walks like a duck and quacks like a duck, then it is a duck

  • Python (dynamic, duck typing):

    class Email(object):
    def __init__(self, time_sent, title, body):
        self.time_sent = time_sent
        self.title, self.body = title, body
    def timestamp(): return date2timestamp(self.date)
    def text(): return title + "\n" + body

def SysLog(timestamp, message):
    # dynamically add fields to a no-arg function (lambda: None)
    obj = lambda: None
    obj.text = lambda: message
    obj.timestamp = lambda: make_absolute(timestamp)
    return obj

Note: if a function is called like a class is instantiation
and has attributes (fields) as an object, then a function is that object.

  • R is also dynamically typed, behaving similarly

Static typing & heterogeneous data

Static typing requires a common (super)type (usually interface):

  • Scala (statically typed):

    def processUniformly(data: Seq[TemporalTexter]) = {
  for (tt <- data)
    println(tt.text, tt.timestamp)
}

  • Go (statically typed):

    func processUniformly(data []TemporalTexter) {
    for tt := range data {
        fmt.Println(tt.Text(), tt.Timestamp())
    }
}

Static typing & common interface

  • Scala:

    trait TemporalTexter {
    def timestamp: Long
    def text: String
}

  • Go:

    type TemporalTexter interface {
    Timestamp() int64
    Text() string
}

Benefit: detects interface mismatch at compile time.

  • less runtime failures (code does not run unless it type-checks)

Nominal vs Structural types

  • Scala (nominal typing = declare the interface via extends/with):

    class SysLog(secElapsed: Double, val text: String)
    extends TemporalTexter {
  def timestamp: Long = absTime(secElapsed)
  // NOTE: "val text" effectively does: def text = this.text
}
class Email(timeSent: Date, title: String, body: String)
    extends TemporalTexter {
  def timestamp = date2timestamp(timeSent)
  def text = title+"\n"+body
}

  • Go (structural typing only = just implement the methods):

    type SysLog struct{ secElapsed float64; message string }
func (self *SysLog) Timestamp() int64 { ... }
func (self *SysLog) Text() string { return self.message; }

type Email struct{ timeSent Date; title, body string }
func (self *Email) Timestamp() int64 { ... }
func (self *Email) Text() string { return title+"\n"+body; }

Type-safe duck typing

If it walks like a duck and quacks like a duck, then it is a duck

  • Scala (via structural types):

    type TemporalTexter = {
    def timestamp: Long
    def text: String
}
    • type SysLog/Email not have to extend TemporalTexter
    • only need methods/fields text and timestamp of compatible types

  • Go (uses structural typing for interfaces):

    type TemporalTexter interface {
    Timestamp() int64
    Text() string
}

Benefit: compile-time guarantees without the burden of tagging

Strong vs weak typing

  • R is weakly typed, allowing type coercion:

    • 2.0 == "2"  # == TRUE
3.0 < "3.0" # == TRUE
list("0") == 0  # == TRUE
list("O") == 0  # == NA (warning: NAs introduced by coercion)
v = c(3L, 1.5)  # == [3.0 1.5] (3 coerced from integer to double)
v[[3]] = "ab"  # == ["3" "1.5" "ab"] (all numbers become chars)
    • simplifies lenient data handling ("let it guess the right type")
    • complicates debugging, as unintended conversions may happen early
      • some numeric computation may silently succeed on strings (e.g., +)

More details in my paper: Evaluating the Design of the R Language
@ European Conference on Object-Oriented Programming.

Strong vs weak typing

  • Python, Scala and Go are strongly typed, allowing:

    • widening conversion only (no loss of precision)

      # Python
i, r = 3, 1.5
i + r  # i promoted to float, (i + r) typed as float
i = r  # NOTE: type of i is now float

// Scala
var (i, r) = (3, 1.5)
i + r  // typed as Double
r = i  // i promoted to Double
i = r  // COMPILE ERROR: type mismatch; found: Double(1.5)
       //                            required: Int

    • no conversion; e.g., Go

      i, real := int32(3), 1.5
i + r  // COMPILE ERROR: mismatched types int32 and float64
r = i  // COMPILE ERROR: cannot use i (type int32) as type
       //                             float64 in assignment

Integer types

  • integers have arbitrary precision in Python

    print(3 ** 42)  # 3 to the power of 42
# prints 109418989131512359209 correctly

  • unlike real numbers (as usual)

    real = 3.0 ** 42  # == 1.0941898913151237e+20
print(int(real))
# prints 109418989131512365056 (incorrect)

  • may overflow in R/Scala/Go, unless we use a "big" integer type

    • BigInt in Scala; also provides natural operator syntax (+, *, etc.)
    • big.Int in Go, but requires method calls for operations (Add, etc.)
    • requires a 3rd-party library in R (e.g., gmp)

Complex numbers

  • fully supported in Go and R
    • built-in types
    • operations supported by standard library

Go:

import . "math/cmplx"   ...
a := 2 - 3i
fmt.Print(Exp(a) / Pow(a, 2))
b := Abs(Sqrt(a) + 2)
fmt.Print(Log(complex(-b, 0)))

R:

a <- complex(real = 2, imag = -3)
cat(exp(a) / a^2)
b <- abs(sqrt(a) + 2)
cat(log(as.complex(-b)))

Complex numbers (cont'd)

  • Python's complex is a built-in type but unsupported by many functions:
    • exp
    • log
    • trigonometric functions

Python:

from numpy import *  # import functions that work on complex

a = 2 - 3j
print(exp(a) / a**2)
b = abs(sqrt(a) + 2)
print(log(complex(-b, 0)))

Note: Python requires a 3rd-party library for a full support.

Slices and Growable Arrays/Vector

  • no need to specify the size in advance
  • appending an element takes amortized O(1) time
  • random access in O(1) time

Example use case: Read data, filter it and extract a subset

R:

  • no built-in data type supports O(1)-time append
    • exception is pairlist which is limited to R interpreter

Scala:

  • almost every collection that is a subtype of IndexedSeq, e.g.:
    • Vector
    • StringBuilder
    • Range

Slicing Growable Arrays/Vector

Python:

def get_middle(slice, k):
    offset = len(slice) // 2 - k // 2
    return slice[offset : offset + k]
  • O(k) space (and time), because data is copied

Go:

func getMiddle(slice []Data, k int) []Data {
    offset := len(slice) / 2 - k / 2
    return slice[offset : offset + k]
}
  • constant time (and space), because data is shared
    • only boundaries (begin/end index) are copied

More details in my paper: Flexible Data Views: Design and Implementation
@ Int'l Workshop on Libraries, Languages and Compilers for Programming

Vectors

  • mutation is very efficient in Scala, it runs in sublinear time

    val n = 10000000
val (original, t0) = time((1 to n).toVector)

// update element at index n/3 with the element at index n/2
val (variant1, t1) = time(original.updated(n/3, original(n/2)))

// update element at index n/2 with the element at index 0
val (variant2, t2) = time(original.updated(n/2, original(0)))

// WOW, the LAST two lines execute ~16000x faster the FIRST two
println(s"update is ${t0 / (t1 + t2)} faster than create")

  • unlike the in-place update of original, it enables parallelism

    val Seq(result1, result2) = Await.result(Future.sequence(Seq(
  process(variant1),
  process(variant2))
), Duration.Infinite)

Vectors

  • in R updating a single element takes linear time if data is shared

    n <- 10000000; time <- function(x) system.time(x)[["elapsed"]]

t0 <- time({orig <- c(1:n)})  # or seq.int(n) or seq(1, n)
t1 <- time({var1 <- orig; var1[[n/3]] <- orig[[n/2]]})
t2 <- time({var2 <- orig; var2[[n/2]] <- orig[[1]]})

# UHH, the LAST two lines are 0.51-1.77 faster than the FIRST
cat("update is", t0 / (t1 + t2), "faster than create\n")

  • so-called Copy-on-Write (CoW)

    • before var1/var2 is changed, a copy of original is made
    • not needed if data is unique

  • the first index is 1 (not 0 as in Scala/Python/Go)

Vectors

  • in Python and Go, lists and slices can only be updated in-place efficiently

Python:

from time import time as now
def time(f): t0 = now(); ret = f(); return ret, now()-t0

def updated(src, i, x):
    dst = src.copy()
    dst[i] = x
    return dst

n = 10000000
orig, t0 = time(lambda: list(range(1, n+1)))
var1, t1 = time(lambda: updated(orig, n//3, orig[n//2]))
var2, t2 = time(lambda: updated(orig, n//2, orig[0]))

# as expected, creation is 1.03x faster than update
print("update is", t0 / (t1 + t2), "faster than create")

String manipulation

  • Strings are immutable in Python, R, Go and Scala
  • modifications (updates) require linear-time copying

String manipulation example

Problem: In a message given as a string, assuming all numbers are integers
and consist of arabic numerals (digits 0 through 9),
convert the numbers to US/GB (English) format.

Note: e.g., 7,654,321 may have been written as:

  • 7 654 321 in Canadian/French
  • 7 654.321 in German
  • 7.654.321 in Spanish/Italian

Algorithm: replace dots and spaces surrounded by digits with commas.

In-place mutation using a buffer

Scala (easy):

  • use StringBuffer, which allows updates at a random index via setChar

Go (hard):

  • use bytes.Buffer, but more tricky because no random access

    • each character is a variable number of bytes (even in string)

String slices and (con)catenation

Python (a naive solution):

def converted(s):
    for i, _ in enumerate(s):
        if s[i] in (".", " ") and 0 < i < len(s)-1 and \
                "0" <= s[i-1] <= "9" and "0" <= s[i+1] <= "9":
            s = s[:i] + "," + s[i+1:]
    return s

Time complexity: O(N^2); consider a huge number in non-US/GB format

  • 2 new string contents of length O(N) created per replacement:
    • s1 = s[:i] + ","
    • s2 = s1 + s[i+1:]

Breaking and joining strings

Python (a linear-time solution):

def converted(s):
    i, chars = len(s)-1, list(s)  # break s into characters
    while i > 1:
        i -= 1
        if (chars[i] == "." or chars[i] == " ") and \
                "0" <= chars[i-1] <= "9" and \
                "0" <= chars[i+1] <= "9":
            chars[i] = ","
    return "".join(chars)

Note: May use 50x extra memory to hold elements of chars

3*sys.getsizeof("4") + sys.getsizeof(",")  # == 200 (~50 byte/char)

Example of worst-case input: 444 444 444 ... (1 byte/char if ASCII)

n=10000;
sys.getsizeof("444 " * n) / (len("444 ") * n)  # == 1.001225

Avoiding accumulation of intermediate data

Using generators in Python:

def converted(s):
    return "".join(converted_chars(s))

def converted_chars(s):
    for i, _ in enumerate(s):
        if s[i] in (".", " ") and 0 < i < len(s)-1 and \
                "0" <= s[i-1] <= "9" and "0" <= s[i+1] <= "9":
            yield ","
        else:
            yield s[i]

Note: a generated character (using yield) is consumed on the fly

  • only O(1) extra memory (because enumerate is also a generator)

Avoiding accumulation of intermediate data

A shorter Python code using inline generators and ternary if:

def converted(s):
    return "".join(
        ("," if s[i] in (".", " ") and 0 < i < len(s)-1 and \
            "0" <= s[i-1] <= "9" and "0" <= s[i+1] <= "9" \
         else s[i]) for i, _ in enumerate(s)
    )

Syntax:

(EXPR(x) for x in ITERABLE)  # returns a generator that yields EXPR(x)

EXPR_T if COND else EXPR_F   # returns EXPR_T/F if COND is True/False

Regular Expressions (syntax & APIs)

Another way of replacing each space/dot surrounded by digits with , via:

  • lookbehind and lookahead (in R, Python, Scala):

    gsub(perl = TRUE, "(?<=[0-9])[ .](?=[0-9])", ",", s)  # R

import re                                        # Python
pat = re.compile(r"(?<=[0-9])[ .](?=[0-9])")
pat.sub(",", s)

import scala.util.matching._
val pat = raw"(?<=[0-9])[ .](?=[0-9])".r
pat.replaceAllIn(s, ",")

  • using capturing groups (the only option in Go)

    import "regexp"   ...
pat := regexp.MustCompile(`([0-9])[ .]([0-9])`)
pat.ReplaceAllString(msg, "$1,$2")

Regular Expression comparative overview

  • Python supports a user-friendly style containing comments & whitespace

    pat = re.compile(r"""
    (?<=[0-9])  # lookbehind: matches the preceding digit
    [ .]        # consume a space or a dot
    (?=[0-9])   # lookahead: matches the following digit
    """, re.VERBOSE)
  • Go only allows subset of the syntax that runs in linear time
    • performance proportional to the size of input
    • easily predictable performance compared to Python/R/Scala
  • R does not support compiling regular expressions
    • performance penalty if multiple inputs are matched/substituted
    • accepts multiple strings at once (must fit in memory)

Functions

  • Anonymous (useful as expressions) supported by:

    • Go

      func(param1 string, param2 int) (string, bool) { ...
    return STR_EXPR, BOOL_EXPR
}

    • Scala

      (param1: String, param2: Int) => { ...
  (STR_EXPR, BOOL_EXPR)  // return type inferred
}

    • R

      function(param1, param2) { ... (STR_EXPR, BOOL_EXPR) }

    • Python - only without statements (...)

      lambda param1, param2: STR_EXPR, BOOL_EXPR

  • Named unsupported in R (unlike Python, Go, Scala)

Higher-order functions & Closures

E.g., model a data source that generates a stream of Fibonacci numbers

Go:

func fib() func() int {
    a, b := 0, 1
    return func() int {
        a, b = b, a+b
        return a
    }
}

Scala:

def fib() = {
    var (a, b) = (0, 1)
    () => val c=a+b; a=b; b=c; a
}

Note: the last expression is returned in Scala (and R)

Higher-order functions & Closures

E.g., model a data source that generates a stream of Fibonacci numbers

Python:

def fib():
    a, b = 0, 1
    def ret():
        nonlocal a, b
        a, b = b, a+b
        return a
    return ret

R:

fib <- function() {
    ab <- c(0, 1)
    function() {
        ab <<- c(ab[[2]], sum(ab))
        ab[[1]]
    }
}

Note: <<- is a non-local assignment (e.g, outside the function)

Call by name & Inversion of Control (IoC)

Use case: Create a function that executes some code multiple times.

  • Scala:

    def repeat(n: Int)(code: =>Unit) =
  for (i <- 0 until n) code

val f = fib()
repeat(5) {
    println("Next Fibonacci number:", f())
}

  • In other languages, parameter code would need to be a function, e.g.:

    repeat := func(n int, runCode func()) {
    for i := 0; i < n; i++ { runCode() }
}

f := fib()
repeat(5, func() {
    fmt.Println("Next Fibonacci number:", f())
})

A short introduction to Cross-Validation (CV)

  • in data science, a simple way to validate a model is to split data into:

    1. test set (only used for validation)
    2. training set (only used for training)
  • what if the test set contains useful information not present in training?

  • a cross-validation technique does this multiple times

k-fold cross-validation (copyright Wikimedia foundation/Wikipedia)

Patterns following the IoC principle

func CrossValidateKFold(k int,  // XXX: k is specific to this strategy
    sample []Data,
    evalTestAfterTraining func([]Data, []Data) Accuracy  // IoC
) Accuracy
  • Dependency Injection (avoid a fixed cross-validation strategy):

type Validator = func([]Data,CrossValidator) Accuracy

  • Factory (do not require the number of rounds of CV):

type CrossValidator = func([]Data) TestTrainSplitter

var validate Validator
accuracy := validate(sample, NewKFold(3))

  • Generator (revert the control by avoiding evalTestAfterTraining):

type TestTrainSplitter = func(*[]Data,*[]Data) bool

Pass by value vs pass by reference

Example: Go slices are passed by value but their underlying data by reference

func NewKFold(k int) CrossValidator {
    return func(sample []Data) TestTrainSplitter {
        i, n := 0, (len(sample)+k-1)/k
        return func(testSet *[]Data, trainingSet *[]Data) bool {
            if i+n > len(sample) {
                n = len(sample) - i
            }
            *testSet = sample[i : i+n]
            *trainingSet = append(
                append([]Data(nil), sample[:i]...), sample[i+n:]...)
            i += n
            return i-n < len(sample)
        }
    }
}
  • Python, Scala and R are pass by value only, but using references
    • cannot reassign variables passed as testSet/testData (must return new)
    • R copies on mutation (no true references except environments)

Testing by example in Go

func Example3FoldCrossValidation() {
    cv := NewKFold(3)
    split := cv([]Data{10, 20, 30, 40, 50})
    var test, training []Data
    for split(&test, &training) {
        fmt.Println(test, training)
    }
    // Output:
    // [10 20] [30 40 50]
    // [30 40] [10 20 50]
    // [50] [10 20 30 40]
}

Output of go -v test:

=== RUN   Example3FoldCrossValidation
--- PASS: Example3FoldCrossValidation (0.00s)
ok      command-line-arguments  0.003s

Note: in other languages we need to write "boilerplate" code

  • construct expected results as data types, and compare them

Concurrency

Python:

  • multi-threading is an afterthought, Python interpreter often waits on Global Interpreter Lock

  • single-threaded by design, quoting the creator of Python:

    It isn't Easy to Remove the GIL... I also don't expect it to go away until
    someone other than me goes through the effort of removing it,
    and showing that its removal doesn't slow down single-threaded Python code.

Go:

  • concurrency is a first-class citizen
    • (I/O) channels to pass data among different goroutines
      • unbuffered (similar to UNIX pipes) or unbuffered (similar to queue)
    • goroutine use the optimal number of threads; millions run efficiently
      • more lightweight than thread, with faster context switching

Intro task revisited: merging data sources

Suppose we want to analyze messages from several data sources:

  1. Yelp reviews
  2. Twitter posts
  3. public Facebook posts

Example analyses:

  • what are the keywords of hot topics (similar to earlier example)?
  • who are the first users that mentioned something?
  • how many users mentioned something on each day?

Using Go channels for data flow

Interfaces for uniformly data access:

type Message interface {
    Text() string
    Timestamp() int64
    Author() string
}

type DataSource interface {
    Fetch(msgs chan<- Message)  // output channel
}

Analysis accepts messages as input and produces reports as output:

func analyze(msgQueue <-chan Message, reports chan<- Report) {
    for msg := range msgQueue {
        if ... {
            reports <- SummarizeData(...)
        }
    }
}

Using Go routines for scalable data pipelines

// parallelize & merge data fetching (slow)
msgQueue := make(chan Message, 100)  // |buffer| = 100
for dataSource := range []DataSource{
    twitter.NewFetcher(),
    reddit.NewFetcher(),
    ...
} {                                // NOTE: "go" starts a goroutine
    go dataSource.Fetch(msgQueue)  //  and immediately returns
}

// concurrently run the analysis, creating reports
reports := make(chan string)  // unbuffered (always blocks)
go analyze(msgQueue, reports)

// collect reports (blocking)
for report := range reports {
    println(report)
}
  • parallelized fetching
  • on-line analysis may start before fetching finishes
  • reports are printed on the fly, as soon as they are produced

Recursion

E.g.: Using the operating system's API (function) for
enumerating the contents (files and directories) of a directory (folder),
count the files matching a certain criteria.

 Private
    secret
 README.md
 Work
     Attorney-Smith_notes.txt
     BusinessMeeting_2017-07-07.docx
     TODO
         contact-partners
         handle-complaints

Natural solution (Python):

def count(dir, match):
    s = 0
    for entry in os.scandir(dir):  # 1 entry in memory at a time
        if entry.is_dir(follow_symlinks=False):
            s += count(entry.path, match)
        elif match(entry):
            s += 1
    return s

Recursion (cont'd)

Solution (Go):

func count(d string, match func(os.FileInfo) bool) (s int64) {
    f, _ := os.Open(d)
    defer f.Close()
    for es, _ := f.Readdir(1); len(es) != 0; es, _ = f.Readdir(1) {
        entry := es[0]
        if entry.IsDir() {
            s += count(filepath.Join(d, entry.Name()), match)
        } else if match(entry) {
            s += 1
        }
    }
    return
}

Limitations of recursion

  • Many languages have a very limited stack size by default

    • Python raises RecursionError for >1000 nested (unfinished) function calls calls
      • e.g., consider count and path subdir1/subdir2/.../subdir1001/matching-file
    • 1024KB in Scala (assuming it runs on 64-bit Java 8)

  • If an upper bound is known, recursion depth can be increased

    • dynamically (once the program is running)

      options(expressions=123456)  # R
sys.setrecursionlimit(123456)  # Python

    • statically

      scala -J-Xss3g  # set to 3 GB

Eliminating recursion using a state stack

A non-recursive count equivalent in Python:

def count(dir, match):
    s = 0
    stack = [(dir, os.scandir(dir))]
    while stack:
        dir, entry_iter = stack.pop()
        try:
            entry = next(entry_iter)
            if entry.is_dir():
                stack.append((entry.path, iter(os.scandir(entry.path))))
            elif match(entry):
                s += 1
            stack.append((dir, entry_iter))
        except StopIteration:
            pass
    return s
  • Current state (dir, entry_iter) is pushed after next
    • effectively models a step in the for loop of the recursive count

Benchmarking

Complete source code in Go

func Fib(n int) int {
    if n < 2 {
        return n
    }
    return Fib(n-1) + Fib(n-2)
}

func BenchmarkFib(b *testing.B) {
    for _, bm := range []struct{ name string; n int }{
        {"base case (n=0)", 0}, {"base case (n=1)", 1},
        {"tiny n    (n=4)", 4}, {"small n   (n=8)", 8},
        {"medium n (n=16)", 16}, {"large n (n=32)", 32},
    } {
        b.Run(bm.name, func(b *testing.B) {
            for i := 0; i < b.N; i++ {
                Fib(bm.n)
            }
        })
    }
}

Parsing & Serialization

  • JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)
  • XML (EXtensible Markup Language)
  • Custom (recursive) data

JSON - eager parsing (all must fit in memory)

  • in the standard library of

    • Python:

      import json
with open("input.json") as file:
    objs = json.load(file)
for i, obj = enumerate(objs):
    process(i, obj)

    • Go:

      import (
    "encoding/json"
    "io/ioutil"
)
...
objs := []interface{}
contents , _ := ioutil.ReadFile("input.json") 
json.Unmarshal(contents, &objs)
for i, obj := objs {
    process(i, obj)
}

JSON - lazy parsing

  • Go provides an incremental parser:
    e.g., useful for streaming JSON:

    var obj interface{}
for d := json.NewDecoder(stream); d.Decode(&obj) == nil; obj = nil {
    process(obj)
}

  • the stream can be created by sending a request over the web:

    resp, _ := http.Get("http://read-json.net/today")
stream := resp.Body

  • the stream can also be established over a dedicated connection:

    conn, _ := net.Dial("tcp", "my.json-stream.server:1234")
stream := bufio.NewReader(conn)

JSON - out-of-the-box (de)serialization

Go:

type Message struct {
    Message string `json:msg`
    User string `json:user`
    Timestamp int64
}

var m Message
...
d.Decode(&m)
...
e.Encode(m)

XML parsing via XPath

Example: Scrape university rankings at a team programming competition

  • assuming the webpage HTML source code is a valid XML containing:

    <table id="medalTable">
  <tbody>
    <!-- rank are within <tr> ... <tr/> tags -->
  </tbody>
</table>

Results of XPath query: .//table[@id='medalTable']/tbody/tr"

<tr><td class="rank">1</td>
    <td class="name">St. Petersburg State University</td>
    <td class="solved r11">11</td></tr>  <!-- (skipped) -->
<tr><td class="rank">3</td>
    <td class="name">Harvard University</td>
    <td class="solved r10">10</td></tr>  <!-- (skipped) -->
  • in Python standard library (see also real-world code:
    • github.com/losvald/univ-rank-scraper

XML parsing via XPath (cont'd)

  • in fact, non-medalists are ranked in a separate table
  • some of them solved the same number of problems but slower
  • XPath to find who solved 9 problems? .//*[td[@class='solved r9']]
    • returns parents (tr) of child tag td with matching attributes

XML - out-of-the-box (de)serialization

Scala:

// serialization
case class Entry(rank: Int, name: String, solved: String)
val entries: Seq[Entry] = ...

for (Entry(rank, name, solved) <- entries) {
  // serialization as XML string
  val xml = <tr>
      <td class="rank">1</td>
      <td class="name">${name}</td>
      <td class="solved ${rank.toString}">${rank.toString}</td>
    </tr>

  // pattern matching XML to extraction each attribute
  for (<td class="{attr}">{text}</td> <- xml \ "td") {
    println(attr, text)
  }
}

Custom parser for a person or relative

Mapping a mention to an entity:

  • valid cases:
    • my mom's father
    • a child of Dan
    • uncle of grandfather of mom's niece
  • seemingly ambiguous but valid
    • the son of Bob's father = the son of [Bob's father]
    • my niece's uncle's nephew = [my niece's uncle]'s nephew
    • Tim Smith, Jr's father = [Tim Smith, Jr]'s father
  • invalid:
    • Ted's father of brother
    • Bill of dad
    • my mom's John's son

Challenges of parsing a person or relative

E.g.: father of mother of father of my Bob's uncle's sister's son

  • recursiveness of the data (arbitrary deep nesting):
  • names may appear only at certain positions and at most once

Alternatives:

  • write an ad-hoc parser by hand (tedious, hard to modify/evolve)
  • cover only cases with a few 's/ofs (incomplete, error-prone)

Solution proposed:

  1. Write a grammar, e.g.: Parsing Expression Grammar (PEG)
  2. automatically generate a parser out of it using a library/tool

A PEG of a person or relative

  • Base rules:

Name [A-Z] [a-z]* ([ ,]+ [A-Z] [a-z]*)*

Member (("an"/"a"/"the") _)? (Parent / Child
Grandparent / Grandchild / Sibling / Nibling / Pibling)
Parent !"step" ("parent"
/ ("mother" / "mom" "my"?)
/ ("father" / "daddy" / "dad"))
Child "child" / "son" / "daughter"
Grandchild "grand" Child
Grandparent "grand" Parent
Sibling !"step" ("bro" "ther"? / "sis" "ter"? / "sib" "ling"?)
Nibling ("nephew" / "niece")
Pibling ("aunt" / "uncle")

A PEG of a person or relative (cont'd)

  • Top-level rule:

Input Person !. {NOTE: !. is End of Input (EOF)}

  • Auxiliary rules:

_ [ \t]+ {NOTE: non-empty sequence of spaces and/or tabs}
S "'s"

  • Recursive rules:

Person Member Of / Whose Member / Member / Name
Of _ "of" _ ("mine" / Person)

Whose (("my" _)? Member / Name) S _ Whose0 / ("my" _)?
Whose0 Member S _ Whose0 / &Member

{NOTE: Member is matched at the end but not captured (&)}

How to work with a PEG parser in Go?

  1. Install pigeon: go get -u github.com/mna/pigeon

  2. Copy-paste the previous rules (without notes) into a .peg file:

    {
package main  // Your Go code between {} will be left as is
}
// PEG RULES HERE ...

  3. Generate a Go file that defines Parse method:

    pigeon -o parser.go parser.peg

  4. Call Parse (needs an import if it is from a different package):

    result, err := Parse("", []byte(input))  // parse a string
result, err := Parse(inputFile, nil)     // parse a file

How to work with a PEG parser in Scala?

  1. Load parboiled2 ("org.parboiled" %% "parboiled" % "2.1.4")

  2. Write PEG rules directly in Scala; type-safe but more verbose:

    import org.parboiled2._
class FamilyParser(var input: ParserInput = "") extends Parser {
  def InputLine = rule { Person ~ EOI }
  // ... more rules ...
  def ` ` = rule { oneOrMore(ch(' ') | ch('\t')) }
  def Whose = rule { (optional("my"~` `)~Memb | Name)~S~` `~Whose0
                    | optional("my"~` `) }
  def Whose0: Rule0 = rule { Memb~S~` `~Whose0 | &(Memb) }
}

  3. Instantiate the parser, then run the top-level InputLine rule:

    val parser = new FamilyParser  // could give input as param
parser.input = input; parser.InputLine.run() match {
  case Success(result) => ...                  }

How to work with a PEG parser in Python?

  1. Install parsimonious: pip3 install parsimonious

  2. Write PEG rules as a Python string; might fail at run-time

    peg = """
    InputLine = Person
    # ... more rules ...
    _ = ~"[ \t]+"
    Whose = (("my" _)? Memb / Name) S _ Whose0 / ("my" _)?
    Whose0 = Member S _ Whose0 / &Memb
"""

  3. Instantiate the parser, then parse one or more inputs

    from parsimonious.grammar import Grammar
parser = Grammar(peg)      # MAY FAIL if invalid PEG
result = grammar.parse(input)  # may raise exception
